05660nam a22007935i 9781526103031DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152013xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815261030317 a10.7765/97815261030312doi  a(DE-B1597)659120  a(OCoLC)960163122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB 4aPN3435b.G67 2013eb 7aLIT0240402bisacsh04a809.3872922300aGothic kinship /ced. by Agnes Andeweg, Sue Zlosnik. 1aManchester : bManchester University Press, c[2015] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors -- tIntroduction -- t1 Matriarchal picture identification in first-wave British Gothic fiction -- t2 Those most intimately concerned’ -- t3 The madwoman in the attic of Labuwangi -- t4 Seed from the east, seed from the west, which one will turn out best? -- t5 ‘Children misbehaving in the walls!’ or, Wes Craven’s suburban family values -- t6 Fathers, friends, and families -- t7 Sisterhood is monstrous -- t8 The political uncanny of the family -- t9 Violent households -- t10 ‘As much a family as anyone could be, anywhere ever’ -- t11 Gothic half-bloods -- t12 ‘They fuck you up’ – revaluations of the family in contemporary British horror film -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the preoccupation of Gothic storytelling with the family has often been observed, it invites a more systematic exploration. Gothic kinship brings together case studies of Gothic kinship ties in film and literature and offers a synthesis and theorisation of the different appearances of the Gothic family.Writers discussed include early British Gothic writers such as Eleanor Sleath and Louisa Sidney Stanhope as well as a range of later authors writing in English, including Elizabeth Gaskell, William March, Stephen King, Poppy Z. Brite, Patricia Duncker, J. K. Rowling and Audrey Niffenegger. There are also essays on Dutch authors (Louis Couperus and Renate Dorrestein) and on the film directors Wes Craven and Steven Sheil.Arranged chronologically, the various contributions show that both early and contemporary Gothic display very diverse kinship ties, ranging from metaphorical to triangular, from queer to nuclear-patriarchal. Gothic proves to be a rich source of expressing both subversive and conservative notions of the family.Gothic kinship will be of interest to academics and students of European and American Gothic in literature and film, gender studies and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFamilies in motion pictures. 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre)xHistory and criticism. 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aKinship in literature. 0aKinship in motion pictures. 4aGothic 2017. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  a18th-21st c.  aBlood ties.  aFamily.  aFilm.  aGothic.  aLiterature.1 aAndeweg, Agnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndeweg, Agnes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuikema, Rosemarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Ranita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Kamilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaefele-Thomas, Ardel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Bernice M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuéma, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlegel, Johannes, econtributor.